On studying the fluorescence property of BTSC-CDs, it was found that the fluorescence emission exhibited excitation-dependent property from 320 to 450 nm (Fig. 5
                        a), which was probably related to different energy levels and emissive traps on the BTSC-CDs surface resulting by the different functional groups. Varying λex, the largest λem was obviously shifted with the increasing λex from 415 to 510 nm. When the excitation wavelength was 360 nm, the maximum fluorescence intensity was presented and the optimum λem was at 450 nm (Fig. 5b). And the fluorescence lifetime of BTSC-CDs was obtained to be 1.42 × 10−8 s (Fig. 5c). Furthermore, to get the good fluorescence stability of the labeled CDs, some impacts were studied, such as pH, buffer system and ionic strength (Fig. 6
                        ). Fig. 6a showed that BTSC-CDs had excellent stability under different pH conditions. Considering further researches, pH = 7.4 was selected for all subsequent detection assays. At the same pH value (pH = 7.4), the BTSC-CDs owned the strongest fluorescent intensity in the PBS buffer system (Fig. 6b). In coexistence with different NaCl concentrations, the fluorescence intensities were little changed even the NaCl concentration up to 1.0 M (Fig. 6c), these would be advantageous in real-world applications.

To elucidate the detecting mechanism, adding Cu2+ into the CDs, only a small fluorescence change occurred at the excitation of 360 nm, and yet with the addition of the same concentration of Cu2+ into the BTSC-CDs, the emission intensity weakened obviously. As is known, nitrogen atom has the coordinating ability with Cu2+, CS and CO of BTSC-CDs are also effective coordination sites for heavy metal ions [38]. In the BTSC-CDs structure, there are plenty of them, which all enhance the coupling capability between BTSC-CDs and Cu2+. The complexation between them may cause fluorescence quenching of the BTSC-CDs. This speculation was proved by its Stern-Volmer equation. The equation was F0/F = 0.9988 + 0.7190 [Q] (R2 = 0.9987, n = 7) (F and F0: the fluorescence intensities of the BTSC-CDs solution in existence with and without Cu2+, [Q] is [Cu2+]). The Stern-Volmer constant was 7.19 × 105 L/mol. As the fluorescence lifetime was 1.42 × 10−8 s, the quenching constant was calculated to be 5.06 × 1013 (Stern-Volmer constant/the fluorescence lifetime), which was significantly bigger than 2.0 × 1010 L/mol s−1, the maximum diffusion quenching rate constant of all quenchers, hinting that a static quenching had occurred because of the reaction of BTSC-CDs with Cu2+ to form a ground-state complex. Moreover, we also used the Density Functional Theory (DFT) calculations to ascertain the possible binding of Cu2+ to BTSC. All calculations were performed by Gaussian 09 program [39]. The computational model of BTSC was determined according to the useful groups NH, OH, CS and CO. First, the geometric structures of possible complexations of Cu2+ with BTSC-CDs had been obtained using B3LYP/6–31G(d)/SDD(Cu) level. The optimized geometries and calculated interaction energy (Eint) of the complexes were shown in Fig. 7
                        a. According to DFT, the more negative the interaction energy, the stronger the binding force. The calculated Eint value of −400.4 kcal/mol suggested that the Cu2+ was more likely to coordinate with oxygen of OC and SC from two BTSC-CDs. Therefore, the Eint values of the representative Na+, Ca2+, Fe3+ and Zn2+ complex by this coordination were further calculated (Table 1
                        ). The larger Eint absolute value of Cu2+ complex than other metal ions complex explained that the BTSC-CDs had higher selectivity to Cu2+. And the UV–vis spectra of the BTSC-CDs solutions were also offered another evidence for the mechanism (Fig. 7b). Adding different metal ions into BTSC-CDs solutions, the UV–vis spectra changed little except Cu2+, and a newly emerging peak at 261 nm validated a new material generating, that was to say a reaction between the probe and Cu2+ was happened.

To evaluate the sensitivity of the probe towards Cu2+, a certain amount of Cu2+ was added into the aqueous solution of BTSC-CDs till the concentration of Cu2+ reached 50 μM, the fluorescence decreased progressively (Fig. 9
                        a). Cu2+ could remarkably quench the fluorescence, and the quenching was also captured by naked eyes under ultraviolet light (inset of Fig. 9a). The fluorescence intensities were also dropped linearly with the increase of the concentrations of Cu2+ within the 0.2–30 μM range and the corresponding equation was y = 752.81–21.25x (R2 = 0.9981) (Fig. 9b). The detection limit was calculated to be 5.05 nM (3σ). As a novel sensing system, the probe also exhibited a higher or comparable sensitivity to Cu2+ than the other nanosensors (Table 2
                        ) [40–48].
